  "prompt": "What is an authoritarian democracy?",
  "response": "An authoritarian democracy is a political system that combines elements of democratic procedure with authoritarian governance. In this type of system, while some democratic institutions like elections exist, the actual practice of governance is characterized by significant restrictions on political freedoms, strong centralized control, and limited genuine political competition. Key features often include:\n\n1. Formal democratic structures (elections, parliaments)\n2. Restricted political participation\n3. Limited freedom of speech and press\n4. Strong executive power\n5. Suppression of opposition\n6. Controlled or manipulated electoral processes\n\nExamples might include countries like Russia, Turkey, and Venezuela, where nominally democratic systems coexist with significant authoritarian practices.",
